North Korea says it will “no way” be disarmed unilaterally without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that the extension of sanctions deepens distrust of the United States, and that under such circumstances the country would in no way be able to abandon its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho said at the annual UN General Assembly that North Korea took “substantial goodwill measures” last year, such as ending nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site and a commitment not to distribute nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we don't see the appropriate reaction from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will not be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
Although Ri reiterated North Korea’s familiar complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for gradual steps, his statement proved important because it did not reject the unilateral denuclearization that Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ree referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between the current US president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim called for work on “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking the formal end of the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must initially abandon nuclear weapons.
Washington is also resisting calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization at first’ and increases the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal forcibly, and even object to ‘declaring the end of the war’,” Ri said.
“To believe that sanctions can put us on our knees is an impossible dream of those who do not know us.
But the problem is that the extension of sanctions deepens our distrust.”
Ree did not mention the plans of a second summit between Kim and Trump, at which the US leader stressed at the UN early the week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings of Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If South Korea, not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not go into such a dead end."
Despite this, the tone of Ree's speech was sharply different from last year when he told the General Assembly that targeting North Korea's missiles on the U.S. mainland was inevitable after Trump called Kim a "missile man" who wanted to commit suicide.
This year, Trump, who threatened to “fully destroy” North Korea last year, praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but said much more needs to be done and sanctions should remain in force until North Korea’s denuclearization.
Trump said on Wednesday that he did not set a time frame for this: “It will take two years, three years or five months — it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and steadily until we see complete, final, confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to block funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear programs and ballistic missiles.
Pompeo met Ree on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for the second summit.
