The National Trust will observe the secret life of bats
A new study conducted on land ownership in the Scottish Highlands aims to establish how bats use the landscape in search of food.
Scientists hope that the data obtained will help shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals in order to carry out measures to preserve them in the future.
In the gardens of Inveryu in Wester Ross, scientists of the National Trust of Scotland will observe such species as netopir dwarf and netopir pygmey, as well as eared ordinary and water night.
Special registrars will be placed in strategic locations in land ownership to observe bat behavior during the season.
Employees and volunteers of the National Trust of Scotland will also conduct mobile research using hand detectors.
Expert analysis of all recorded sounds will help to establish the frequency and affiliation of bat screams.
It is then planned to develop a detailed residence card of animals and prepare a report to link animal behavior to their habitat.
Rob Dewar, an adviser on nature protection at the National Trast of Scotland, hopes the results of the study will help determine which areas of residence are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help assess the effectiveness of habitat care measures (for example, the formation of meadows) and determine the optimal methods for preserving forests for bats and other related species.
Over the past century, bat populations have declined significantly in Scotland and in the UK.
They are threatened with active construction and development of territories, which deprives them of nesting places.
Other negative factors include wind installations and lighting, adhesive paper for flies, chemical processing of building materials, as well as attacks of domestic cats.
The bats are not actually blind.
However, due to night hunting, ears more effectively help them catch prey than their eyes.
They use a complex echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles on the flight trajectory.
The National Trast of Scotland, which cares for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of particular importance and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, take bat problems very seriously.
Ten specially trained experts regularly conduct research, nesting site checks, and sometimes even rescue operations.
The efforts of the organization even created the first and only bat reserve in Scotland. It is located on the territory of the town of Triv in the Dumfries and Galloway region. It found refuge for eight of the ten species of bats living in Scotland.
The host manager David Thompson claims that this is the perfect place for them.
“There were excellent conditions for bats on the territory of the city,” he assures.
“There are old buildings, many giant trees and other favorable living conditions.
However, we still need to learn a lot about bats. Thanks to the research we conduct here and elsewhere, we will be able to learn more about what they need to thrive."
He insists that it is very important to check the territory for bats before any technical work, since due to the unintentional destruction of one nesting site for the removal of young, up to 400 females with cubs can die, which is likely to cause the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats and their nests are protected by law. Animals are prohibited to kill, torture or disturb.
Elizabeth Ferrrell, an officer at the Scottish Bat Conservation Center, urged the public to join the organization's efforts.
She said, "We still need to learn a lot about our bats. We have not yet revealed the characteristics of populations of many species."
